HEADWORD: Bilbo
<hw>Bil"bo</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Bilboes</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A rapier; a
sword; so named from <etsep>Bilbao</etsep>, in Spain.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A long bar or bolt of iron with
sliding shackles, and a lock at the end, to confine the feet of
prisoners or offenders, esp. on board of ships.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methought I lay⟦br⟧
Worse than the mutines in the <qex>bilboes</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bilboquet</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
